In C++, a **data model** is simply a structure or class that represents *data + minimal logic*, 
usually designed with **value semantics** (safe, copyable, independent).

building console systems and engines, this is very relevant

---

# 1. Basic Data Model Example

👉 Represent a real-world entity

#include <string>

struct Person {
    std::string name;
    int age;
};

### Usage:

Person p1{"Shiv", 25};
Person p2 = p1;   // value copy

p2.name = "Ram";

✔ `p1` and `p2` are independent
👉 This is **value semantics data model**

---

# 2. Data Model with Behavior (Still Simple)

struct Product {
    std::string name;
    double price;

    double applyDiscount(double percent) const {
        return price - (price * percent / 100);
    }
};

✔ Logic is small and related to data
✔ No heavy dependencies

---

# 3. Immutable Data Model (Very Safe)

👉 Prevent modification after creation

struct Config {
    const int maxUsers;
    const std::string appName;

    Config(int users, std::string name)
        : maxUsers(users), appName(std::move(name)) {}
};

✔ Safer for multi-threading
✔ No accidental changes

---

# 4. Real-World Example (Console App)

### Sensor Data Model

struct SensorData {
    int id;
    double value;
    std::string timestamp;
};

### Usage:

SensorData s1{1, 23.5, "10:30"};
SensorData s2 = s1;  // copy

s2.value = 50.0;

✔ Each sensor reading is independent

---

# 5. Data Model with STL (Common Pattern)

#include <vector>

struct Student {
    std::string name;
    int marks;
};

std::vector<Student> students;

✔ STL containers store **value-type models**

---

# 6. Data Model Passed as Reference (Optimization)

void print(const Person& p) {
    std::cout << p.name;
}

✔ No copy
✔ Still using value model

---

# What NOT to Do (Bad Data Model)

❌ Mixing logic + memory + ownership:


struct BadModel {
    int* data;  // raw pointer ❌
};

👉 Causes:

* Memory leaks
* Complex ownership

✔ Prefer:

struct GoodModel {
    std::vector<int> data;  // safe
};

---

# Key Characteristics of Good Data Models

* Simple structure
* Value semantics
* No raw pointers
* Minimal logic
* Easy to copy
* STL-friendly

